rstanding of the symbolic implications of contagionism marking the boundaries between sick and healthy, familiar and alien, morally pure and impure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCommunicable diseases in literature. 0aContagion (Social psychology). 0aLiterature and medicine. 4aAnsteckung. 4aBakteriologie. 4aKrankheitsnarrative. 4aLiterarische Moderne. 4aMetaphern, medizinische. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aContagionism.  abacteriology.  aillness narratives.  aliterary Modernism.  amedical metaphors.1 aAnz, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriese, Olaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElsaghe, Yahya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGradmann, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Martina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKäser, Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontiel, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRütten, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRütten, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaul, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWald, Priscilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Medicine and Life Sciences 2000-2014 (EN)z9783110238